    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>There is no consensus theory of high mass star formation (HMSF). 
The study of the nearest example of HMSF, Orion BN/KL, enables interpretation of more distant and less resolved regions. However, the presence of complex phenomena has so far prevented us from achieving a complete understanding of BN/KL. 
We propose to observe with ALMA in band 7 the central core of BN/KL in a number of molecular species and continuum emission. 
New ALMA observations will deliver for the first time:
i) a high-fidelity image of the dust continuum emission, providing a complete census of star formation and a first epoch for  protostellar proper motion measurements, enabling a reconstruction of the region dynamical history;
ii) sub-arcsecond images of highly-excited molecular lines in the Hot Core, permitting us to localize precisely the hot gas in the region and unveil its heating mechanism;
iii) a detailed picture of the disk/outflow in Source I, which may enable resolution of rotation in both the disk and the outflow, thus confirming our hypothesis of a magnetocentrifugal origin for its outflow.
A better understanding of Orion BN/KL will permit a significant advance in our understanding of HMSF.</prp:abstract>
